  "title": "Allelic polymorphism in the T cell receptor and its impact on immune responses.",
  "journal": "The Journal of experimental medicine",
  "year": 2010,
  "authors": "Gras S, Chen Z, Miles JJ, Liu YC, Bell MJ, Sullivan LC, Kjer-Nielsen L, Brennan RM, Burrows JM, Neller MA, Khanna R, Purcell AW, Brooks AG, McCluskey J, Rossjohn J, Burrows SR."
 },
 "executive_summary": "This study examined the EBV-specific T cell response restricted by HLA-B*3501 to the HPVGEADYFEY peptide, comparing the commonly selected TRBV9*01 TCR variant (TK3) with the natural allelic variant TRBV9*02, which differs by a single amino acid (Gln55His) near the CDR2\u03b2 loop. Crystal structures of both TCR variants in complex with HLA-B*3501\u2013peptide revealed that the His55 substitution in TRBV9*02 disrupts charge complementarity at the TCR\u2013pMHC interface, impairing recognition of the cognate EBV epitope and explaining why TRBV9*02 is rarely or never selected during this immune response. This finding demonstrates that genetic polymorphism within TCR loci\u2014rather than just HLA variation\u2014can functionally constrain T cell repertoire selection and influence infection outcomes, with implications for understanding variable responsiveness to pathogens and potential links to autoimmunity-associated TCR alleles.",
